<subSubSection id="6DC56513FFE4FFE8E2C2A3F4CF2B777E" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25603698FFE4FFE8E2C2A3F4CC8E7672" blockId="10.[151,1437,150,788]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFE4FFE8E2C2A3F4CF7B75C6" bold="true" box="[199,315,402,428]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus was defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="414E4B69FFE4FFE8E06FA3F4CD4A75C7" author="Adams, P. A." box="[618,778,402,429]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" pagination="215 - 238" refId="ref21987" refString="Adams, P. A. (1967) A review of the Mesochrysinae and Nothochrysinae (Neuroptera: Chrysopidae). Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 135, 215 - 238." type="journal article" year="1967">Adams (1967)</bibRefCitation>
based on the fusion of the forewing RP1 and MA for some distance in its only known specimen, a condition otherwise unknown in 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFE4FFE8E1C2A3D0CA3C75BA" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1910" box="[967,1148,438,464]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nothochrysinae">Nothochrysinae</taxonomicName>
. However, this fusion occurs only in the right forewing (
<figureCitation id="BDE42A1DFFE4FFE8E005A3BCCC17759F" box="[512,599,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1442,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1419]" captionTargetId="figure-207@8.[151,1436,597,1419]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Archaeochrysa sp., specimen NHM.I.26921 (counterpart). NHMUK PI I.26921 image © The Trustees of the Natural History Museum. Scale bar = 3 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6522463" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6522463/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
) and these veins are separate in the left forewing (
<figureCitation id="BDE42A1DFFE4FFE8E694A3BCCAAB759F" box="[1169,1259,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1442,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1419]" captionTargetId="figure-207@8.[151,1436,597,1419]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Archaeochrysa sp., specimen NHM.I.26921 (counterpart). NHMUK PI I.26921 image © The Trustees of the Natural History Museum. Scale bar = 3 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6522463" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6522463/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
). Therefore, we take this fusion to be an aberration, not diagnostic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25603698FFE4FFE8E2C2A045CF2B777E" blockId="10.[151,1437,150,788]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
In general, the preserved forewing venation of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFE4FFE8E0D9A044CDC27656" authorityName="Adams" authorityYear="1967" box="[732,898,546,572]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Dyspetochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFE4FFE8E0D9A044CDC27656" box="[732,898,546,572]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Dyspetochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFE4FFE8E6AFA044CB127656" authorityName="Adams" authorityYear="1967" box="[1194,1362,546,572]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Archaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFE4FFE8E6AFA044CB127656" box="[1194,1362,546,572]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Archaeochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially by the far distal location of the M fork relative to the origin of RP. It is possible that these genera are synonyms, however, the crossvein in the RA space proximad 1r-m considered diagnostic of 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFE4FFE8E68CA00CCB7176EE" authorityName="Adams" authorityYear="1967" box="[1161,1329,618,644]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Archaeochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFE4FFE8E68CA00CCB7176EE" box="[1161,1329,618,644]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Archaeochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is absent in 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFE4FFE8E2B1A0E8CF1A76C2" authorityName="Adams" authorityYear="1967" box="[180,346,654,680]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Dyspetochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFE4FFE8E2B1A0E8CF1A76C2" box="[180,346,654,680]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Dyspetochrysa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this might also be an aberration. Further, the 
<typeStatus id="FA64883AFFE4FFE8E189A0E8CDAE76C2" box="[908,1006,654,680]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">holotype</typeStatus>
and only known specimen of the only species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="E2DF4D1BFFE4FFE8E38DA0D5CC5576A6" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1890" box="[392,533,690,716]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Tribochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vetuscula">
<emphasis id="17ABEA8AFFE4FFE8E38DA0D5CC5576A6" box="[392,533,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">D. vetuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite fragmentary. The validity of the genus is, therefore, tenuous. We prefer, however, to continue to recognize it here based on the diagnosis above, pending better preserved specimens to clarify its position.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
